<subSubSection id="C3236569FFE46A07136CFD5CFE5BD2C4" box="[113,502,655,678]" pageId="37" pageNumber="146" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B8636E2FFE46A07136CFD5CFE5BD2C4" blockId="37.[111,649,586,959]" box="[113,502,655,678]" pageId="37" pageNumber="146">
ETYMOLOGY. — Latin, 
<emphasis id="B94DEAF0FFE46A071245FD5CFE20D2C4" box="[344,397,655,678]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="146">discus</emphasis>
, flat plate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3236569FFE46A07136CFD69FEC1D3DD" pageId="37" pageNumber="146" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B8636E2FFE46A07136CFD69FEC1D3DD" blockId="37.[111,649,586,959]" pageId="37" pageNumber="146">DIAGNOSIS. — Shell, medium large, subcircular, discoidal, translucent, with projecting arcuate, anterior dorsal area. Sculpture of irregularly spaced, low, commarginal lamellae. Ligament large, set into deep groove, nymph straight. Lunule very small. Cardinal teeth indistinct. Anterior lateral teeth short, close to cardinals. Posterior lateral teeth absent or vestigial. Anterior adductor muscle scar long, dorsal portion extended onto the hinge line above the lateral teeth, long ventral part lies close but parallel to the pallial line.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3236569FFE46A07136CFC23FDE5D505" pageId="37" pageNumber="146" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B8636E2FFE46A07136CFC23FF78D46A" blockId="37.[112,648,1008,1383]" box="[113,213,1008,1034]" pageId="37" pageNumber="146">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8636E2FFE46A07136CFBC3FDE5D505" blockId="37.[112,648,1008,1383]" pageId="37" pageNumber="146">
One of the most distinctive features of this genus is the very long anterior adductor muscle scar that extends dorsally onto the hinge line. Although dissimilar in general morphology, 
<taxonomicName id="4C394D61FFE46A0712E7FBBCFF7DD4CB" authorityName="Glover &amp; Taylor" authorityYear="2007" baseAuthorityName="Salisbury" baseAuthorityYear="1934" class="Bivalvia" family="Lucinidae" genus="Lepidolucina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lucinida" pageId="37" pageNumber="146" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="odontotis" status="n. comb.">
<emphasis id="B94DEAF0FFE46A0712E7FBBCFF7DD4CB" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="146">Lepidolucina odontotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27E578BFFE46A0713C5FB5CFE96D4CB" box="[216,315,1167,1193]" pageId="37" pageNumber="146" rank="species">n. comb.</taxonomicNameLabel>
also has an extended anterior muscle scar and projecting lobate anterior dorsal area (
<figureCitation id="13022A67FFE46A0713B6FB1DFE80D48A" box="[171,301,1230,1256]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="34.[113,124,1612,1629]" captionTargetBox="[157,1166,216,1537]" captionTargetId="figure-110@34.[661,1167,667,949]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIG. 21. — A, B, E-H, Lepidolucina venusta (Philippi, 1847) n. comb.; A, B, Isle of Luzon, Philippines (BMNH 1969119/2); A, exterior left valve; B, interior left valve; E, detail of sculpture, Borneo (BMNH 77.4.26.43); F, inner shell margin, Borneo; G, H, detail of hinge teeth, Borneo (BMNH); C, D, L. odontotis (Salisbury, 1934) n. comb., holotype, Sarawak (BMNH 1893.9.1.12-1), interior and exterior of right valve. Scale bars: A-D, 10 mm; E, 1 mm; F, 0.5 mm; G, H, 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5392335" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5392335/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="146">Fig. 21C, D</figureCitation>
). Another lucinid with a dorsally extended adductor scar is 
<taxonomicName id="4C394D61FFE46A071299FB3DFF19D54A" authority="(Philippi, 1848)" baseAuthorityName="Philippi" baseAuthorityYear="1848" class="Bivalvia" family="Lucinidae" genus="Loripes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lucinida" pageId="37" pageNumber="146" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="clausus">
<emphasis id="B94DEAF0FFE46A071299FB3DFDB7D56A" box="[388,538,1262,1288]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="146">Loripes clausus</emphasis>
(Philippi, 1848)
</taxonomicName>
, from the western Indian Ocean, but this species has a prominent, obliquely inset internal ligament, similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C394D61FFE46A071287FA9EFDEDD505" baseAuthorityName="Lamarck" baseAuthorityYear="1818" box="[410,576,1357,1383]" class="Bivalvia" family="Lucinidae" genus="Loripes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lucinida" pageId="37" pageNumber="146" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="lucinalis">
<emphasis id="B94DEAF0FFE46A071287FA9EFDEDD505" box="[410,576,1357,1383]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="146">Loripes lucinalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
